Are you lonely at work?

You're not alone.

Studies shows 82% of employees feel isolated at work â€” thatâ€™s almost everyone.

Most people get wrong think "networking" is just for external relationships.

But internal networks matter more than ever.

In my experience, companies with strong internal networks see better outcomes in employee wellbeing.

So why donâ€™t we do it more?

The problem is most people say "I'll connect with colleagues when I have time."

Sadly, that time never comes.

Instead of waiting for inspiration to network internally:

â€¢ Block off 2-3 hours each week just for internal relationship building
â€¢ Schedule it early in the day (not after you're drained from meetings)
â€¢ Make it a protected habit, like any other important work task

Think beyond your direct team:

â€¢ Connect with project managers (they touch every part of the company)
â€¢ Reach out to people in different departments
â€¢ Build bridges between teams you work with

It can be as simple as:

â€¢ Looking at your company org chart
â€¢ Picking someone you don't know well
â€¢ Sending a short "I noticed your work on [project]. Would love to learn more about what you do.â€

The best workplace relationships don't happen by accident.

They happen by design.

Young professionals, I know youâ€™ve been told that success takes time

but what if I told you that your ability to embrace change could accelerate your growth?

Let me take you back to when I first started my career. I was so excited about what was to come, eager to prove myself. But then, something unexpected happened.

THE MARKET CHANGED.

And by â€œchanged,â€ I mean everything I thought I knew about my industry, my role and even my strategyâ€¦ shifted
(picture this, everything was going in a particular direction and the next thing we saw was the complete opposite; a complete drastic change )

The plan I had worked on for months? No longer relevant. The skills I had just mastered? Now outdated. The strategies I had perfected? Suddenly ineffective.

I was lost. My first instinct was to resist (if you were in my shoes, I'm sure you'd do the same thing ). I wanted to stick to the plan, stay in my comfort zone. But the more I tried to hold on, the more frustrated I became.

Thatâ€™s when I learned my biggest lesson about success:

ï¸Change is the only constant.
If you're going to grow, you need to embrace change. Donâ€™t fight it. When things shift whether itâ€™s a market trend, a new skill set, or a new role; take it as an opportunity to level up, learn and ADAPT.

ï¸Change can push you beyond your limits. The beauty of change is that it forces you to get uncomfortable. In that discomfort, you find new solutions, develop new skills, and discover new strengths. I realized that stepping out of my comfort zone was the best way to expand it.

ï¸Flexibility is your power.
In this fast-paced world, the ability to pivot is more valuable than having a rigid plan. Whether youâ€™re in marketing, project management, or any field, how quickly you adapt is what will set you apart.

It wasnâ€™t easy but once I learned to roll with the punches and adapt to change, everything started to fall into place.

To every young professional out there:
Embrace change. Change can be as small as leveraging social, updating your linkedin headline, revamping your resume
